<message><date> wed, 28 may 2003 11:50:04 +0100 (bst) </date><from> ac.uk </from><to> ac.uk </to><subject><text_normal> ^  ame results </text_normal></subject><content-type> text/plain; charset=us-ascii </content-type><message_body><text_normal> ^ hi  ame , ^ here are the baseline results for my classifier on the lingspam corpus : ^ precision for genuine :  um recall for genuine :  um ^ precision for  ame :  um recall for  ame :  um ^ f1 for genuine :  um f1 for  ame :  um ^ there seems to be some confusion in the literature about the exact definitions of precision and recall for the 2-class classification problem . ^ i define recall as  um (  ame + fn ) and precision as  um (  ame + fp ) ^ where  ame true positive  ame false positive  ame false negative ^ i.e. recall is measuring the number of correctly classified units for class  har against the number missed , whereas precision is measuring the number of correctly classified units for class  har against the total number of class  har classifications made . ^ in some of the literature these measurements are the other way around ! ^ this gives a precision / recall / f1 for each class . ^  ame </text_normal></message_body></message>